{
  "query": "When managing understory vegetation in US forests, how does the effectiveness of herbicide use compare to mechanical removal for amphibian populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies conducted in US forests, mechanical removal and herbicide use for understory vegetation management show different effects on amphibian populations. One randomized, replicated, controlled study in the USA found that mechanical understory reduction resulted in significantly higher numbers of amphibian species compared to plots without treatment, though amphibian abundance was not significantly affected (Action ID: 781). In contrast, three studies in the USA (including two randomized, replicated, controlled studies) found that understory removal using herbicide had no effect or some negative effects on amphibian abundance (Action ID: 778). Additionally, one replicated, site comparison study in Canada found that following logging, wood frog abundance was lower in stands treated with herbicide and planting compared to stands left to regenerate naturally, while American toad abundance was similar between treatments (Action ID: 778).",
