  "query": "When managing understory vegetation in US forests, how does the effectiveness of herbicide use compare to mechanical removal for amphibian populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence from US forests, mechanical removal of understory vegetation appears to have more favorable effects on amphibian populations compared to herbicide use. One randomized, replicated, controlled study in the USA found that mechanical understory reduction resulted in significantly higher numbers of amphibian species, though not abundance, compared to areas without treatment (Action 781). In contrast, three studies in the USA found that understory removal using herbicides had no effect or some negative effects on amphibian abundance (Action 778). Additionally, one replicated, site comparison study in Canada found that following logging, American toad abundance was similar but wood frogs were lower in stands with herbicide treatment and planting compared to stands left to regenerate naturally (Action 778). Forest thinning studies provide additional context, showing that forest management practices can have mixed effects on amphibians, with some species benefiting while others may decline (Action 852).",
