{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits and negative impacts of livestock grazing on agricultural lands for amphibian habitats and populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the action documents, livestock grazing on agricultural lands has mixed documented impacts on amphibian habitats and populations. \n\nRegarding negative impacts: One replicated, randomized, controlled study in wetlands found no difference in abundance of Yosemite toads between areas with cattle excluded and grazed areas (action 1417, 2319). Another replicated, randomized, controlled study in Australia found that ungrazed areas had similar overall reptile and amphibian abundance compared to areas that were grazed, burned or grazed and burned to remove invasive para grass (action 3512). \n\nFor positive impacts of grazing management: Five studies including four replicated studies in Denmark, Estonia and the UK found that habitat management that included reintroduction of grazing increased green toad populations, maintained or increased natterjack toad populations and maintained common toad populations (action 780). However, one replicated, controlled study in the UK found that grazed plots did not have higher abundance of natterjack toads than ungrazed plots and had lower abundance of common toads (action 780).\n\nRegarding grazing cessation impacts: One replicated, site comparison study in the USA found that ungrazed sites had fewer bog turtles than grazed sites, while another study found that juvenile box turtles were present less frequently in ungrazed sites compared to grazed sites (action 3512). One before-and-after study in the USA found that the decline in amphibian species was similar under traditional season-long or intensive-early cattle stocking (action 780).\n\nThe evidence shows context-dependent effects where grazing management can benefit some amphibian species while having neutral or negative effects on others, with outcomes varying by species, habitat type, and grazing intensity.",
