{
  "query": "For amphibian conservation in North America, how do the outcomes of creating new wetlands compare to restoring existing wetlands?",
  "relevant_summary": "For amphibian conservation in North America, studies comparing created and restored wetlands show similar effectiveness patterns. Created wetlands demonstrated varied outcomes in five site comparison studies in the USA that compared them to natural wetlands, with some finding similar numbers of amphibian species, abundance, or communities, while two studies found created wetlands had fewer species or lower abundance and different communities compared to natural wetlands (Action 880). Restored wetlands showed more consistent positive outcomes, with ten site comparison studies in Canada and the USA finding that eight studies showed similar amphibian abundance, numbers of species, and species composition between restored and natural wetlands, while only two found lower numbers or abundance in restored wetlands (Action 879). Both approaches demonstrated colonization success, with created wetlands being colonized by four to 15 amphibian species (Action 880) and restored wetlands being colonized by three to eight amphibian species (Action 879). A global review found that restored and created wetlands had similar or higher amphibian abundance or numbers of species to natural wetlands in 89% of cases (Action 879), while another global review found that created and restored wetlands combined had higher or similar numbers compared to natural wetlands, with 54% showing higher numbers and 35% showing similar numbers (Action 880). Seven of nine studies found that wetland restoration increased numbers of amphibian species with breeding populations establishing in some cases (Action 879). Both approaches were affected by factors including wetland design, vegetation, water levels, surrounding habitat, fish presence, wetland size, proximity to source ponds, and seasonality (Actions 879, 880).",
